  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div xml:id="AN122.1-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">1. talaimakaṉ ciṟaippuṟattāṉākat (C1+6, NL: ciṟaippulittāṉākat) tōḻikkut colluvāḷāyt talaimakaḷ colliyatu (C7v, RK: coṟṟatu).
            [C7, RK: 2. tōḻi colleṭuppat talaimakaḷ colliyatūumāma.]</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. What SHE said as one speaking to the confidante when HE was behind the hedge.
            [2. It is also what SHE said when the confidante took up the word. This song is night tryst.]
            </p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN122.1">
            <lg type="edition">
                <l>irumpiḻi makāriv vaḻuṅkaṉ mūtūr</l>
                <l>viḻaviṉ ṟāyiṉun tuñcā tāku</l>
                <l>malla lāvaṇa maṟukuṭaṉ maṭiyiṉ</l>
                <l>valluraik kaṭuñco laṉṉai tuñcāḷ</l>
                <l>piṇiko ḷaruñciṟai yaṉṉai tuñciṟ</l>
                <l>ṟuñcāk kaṇṇar kāvalar kaṭukuva</l>
                <l>rilaṅkuvē liḷaiyar tuñciṉ vaiyeyiṟṟu</l>
                <l>valañcurit tōkai ñāḷi makiḻu</l>
                <l>maravavāy <supplied>ña</supplied>mali makiḻātu maṭiyiṟ</l>
                <l>pakaluru vuṟaḻnilavuk kāṉṟu vicumpi</l>
                <l>ṉakalvāy maṇṭila niṉṟuviri yu<supplied>m</supplied>mē</l>
                <l>tiṅkaḷ kalcērpu kaṉaiyiruṇ maṭiyi</l>
                <l>ṉilleli valci valvāyk kūkai</l>
                <l>kaḻutuvaḻaṅ kiyāmat taḻitakak kuḻaṟum</l>
                <l>vaḷaikkaṭ cēval vāḷātu maṭiyiṉ</l>
                <l>maṉaicceṟi kōḻi māṇkura liyampu</l>
                <l>mellā maṭinta kālai yorunā</l>
                <l>ṇillā neñcat tavarvā ralarē</l>
                <l>yataṉā</l>
                <l>laripey puṭṭi lārppap pariciṟan</l>
                <l>tāti pōkiya pāypari naṉmā</l>
                <l>ṉocci vēlit titta ṉuṟantaik</l>
                <l>kaṉmutir puṟaṅkāṭ ṭaṉṉa</l>
                <l>paṉmuṭ ṭeṉṟāṟ ṟōḻinaṅ kaḷavē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l>Even when there is no festival, this noisy old town</l> 
                <l>of the sons of dark toddy will not sleep.</l>
                <l>Even when it dozes off, with its rich market streets,</l>
                <l>mother with outspoken, harsh words will not sleep.</l>
                <l>Even when mother, with [her] fettering strict confinement, sleeps,</l>
                <l>the watchmen with sleepless eyes will make haste.</l>
                <l>Even when the young [guards] with shining spears sleep, the sharp-toothed</l>
                <l>dogs with right-curling tails will be excited.</l>
                <l>Even when the loud-mouthed dogs lose [their] excitement [and] doze off,</l>
                <l>the wide round area of the sky stands revealed</l>
                <l>by moonlight almost as bright as day.</l>
                <l>Even when the moon joins the rocks [and] deep darkness falls,</l>
                <l>the strong-mouthed owl that lives on house rats</l>
                <l>will shriek, heart-rending, at midnight when demons roam.</l>
                <l>Even when the male with curved beak silently dozes off,</l>
                <l>the glorious voice of the house cock will sound.</l>
                <l>At the time they all doze off, for one single day,</l>
                <l>the [lover] of [our] restless heart won’t come.</l>
                <l>Therefore,</l>
                <l>like the rocky outer forest</l>
                <l>around Tittaṉ’s Uṟantai, with [its] Nocci hedges,</l>
                <l>for the good horses of leaping gait that went galloping</l>
                <l>in enormous motion so that [their] metal-adorned anklets(?)  rattled,</l>
                <l>a thing of many thorns it is called indeed,  friend, our secret love.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
